To behave as an SMM, the anisotropy barrier must be sufficiently large. In the simplest approximation for transition metal ions with total integer spin, it is given by Ueff=DS2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$U_{\mathrm {eff}} = DS^2$$\end{document}, where D is the axial anisotropy parameter [8, 19] (see next section). The D value depends on the electrostatic interactions between the magnetic center and the organic ligands, and the anisotropic inter-centre interactions (e.g. dipole–dipole coupling). For negative values, spin states with the largest projection along the anisotropy axis are preferred, resulting in a strong easy-axis anisotropy.

